all ioy, pleasure without paine, life without death, euery thing that is good, without any thing that is euill. Amen.

Thirdly, Iohn was greater then the Prophets vnder the lawe, because they prophesied of Christ to come: but Iohn bare record that he was come, being, as Beauxāmis harmon. Tom. 2. fol. 258. & Albert. in loc. & Caluin. Instit. lib. 2. cap. 9. Sect. 5. diuines haue tearmed him, a midling, betweene a Prophet and an Apostle: a propheticall Apostle, and an apostolicall Prophet: T • rtullian. lib. 4. contra Marcio • .
Limes inter vtrumque constitutus, in quo desinerent vetera, & noua inciperent: The Baptist then is more then a Prophet, in pointing him out with the finger;
who is the very center of all the Prophets aime.

